{"schema":"algviz/1","title":"Longest Common Subsequence","topic":"dynamic-programming","code":["public int LongestCommonSubsequence(string a, string b)","{","    int m = a.Length, n = b.Length;","    var dp = new int[m + 1, n + 1];","    for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++)","        for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++)","            dp[i, j] = a[i - 1] == b[j - 1]","                ? dp[i - 1, j - 1] + 1","                : Math.Max(dp[i - 1, j], dp[i, j - 1]);","    return dp[m, n];","}"],"structures":{"dp":{"type":"grid","label":"dp[i, j] = LCS length of a[0..i-1], b[0..j-1]"}},"frames":[{"line":4,"caption":"Base case: an empty prefix shares no subsequence, so row 0 and column 0 are all 0. Fill the rest top-to-bottom, left-to-right.","note":"LCS is the canonical 2D-grid DP. State: dp[i][j] = the LCS length of the first i characters of a and the first j of b. The base cases are free (an empty prefix shares nothing), and every other cell is built from cells above and to the left — so a single forward sweep fills the whole table.","vars":{"a":"\"abcde\"","b":"\"ace\""},"result":null,"states":{"dp":{"type":"grid","rows":6,"cols":4,"cells":[{"key":"r0c0","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r0c1","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r0c2","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r0c3","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r1c0","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r1c1","value":0},{"key":"r1c2","value":0},{"key":"r1c3","value":0},{"key":"r2c0","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r2c1","value":0},{"key":"r2c2","value":0},{"key":"r2c3","value":0},{"key":"r3c0","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r3c1","value":0},{"key":"r3c2","value":0},{"key":"r3c3","value":0},{"key":"r4c0","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r4c1","value":0},{"key":"r4c2","value":0},{"key":"r4c3","value":0},{"key":"r5c0","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r5c1","value":0},{"key":"r5c2","value":0},{"key":"r5c3","value":0}],"rowHeader":["·","a","b","c","d","e"],"colHeader":["·","a","c","e"]}}},{"line":8,"caption":"a[0]='a' == b[0]='a': extend the diagonal. dp[1,1] = dp[0,0] + 1 = 1.","note":"When the current characters match, they can both end a common subsequence, so we extend the best answer from the DIAGONAL cell dp[i-1][j-1] (the LCS of the two shorter prefixes) by 1. The diagonal is the \"use both characters\" move — it is the only transition that actually grows the subsequence.","vars":{"a":"\"abcde\"","b":"\"ace\"","i":1,"j":1},"result":null,"states":{"dp":{"type":"grid","rows":6,"cols":4,"cells":[{"key":"r0c0","value":0,"highlight":"compared"},{"key":"r0c1","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r0c2","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r0c3","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r1c0","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r1c1","value":1,"highlight":"active"},{"key":"r1c2","value":0},{"key":"r1c3","value":0},{"key":"r2c0","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r2c1","value":0},{"key":"r2c2","value":0},{"key":"r2c3","value":0},{"key":"r3c0","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r3c1","value":0},{"key":"r3c2","value":0},{"key":"r3c3","value":0},{"key":"r4c0","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r4c1","value":0},{"key":"r4c2","value":0},{"key":"r4c3","value":0},{"key":"r5c0","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r5c1","value":0},{"key":"r5c2","value":0},{"key":"r5c3","value":0}],"rowHeader":["·","a","b","c","d","e"],"colHeader":["·","a","c","e"]}}},{"line":9,"caption":"'a' != 'c': drop one character, take the better side. dp[1,2] = max(up 0, left 1) = 1.","note":"When the characters differ, at least one of them cannot be in the LCS, so we drop one and keep the better of the two smaller subproblems: dp[i-1][j] (ignore a's char) or dp[i][j-1] (ignore b's char). Taking the max is what guarantees optimality — we never lock in a worse branch.","vars":{"a":"\"abcde\"","b":"\"ace\"","i":1,"j":2},"result":null,"states":{"dp":{"type":"grid","rows":6,"cols":4,"cells":[{"key":"r0c0","value":0,"highlight":"filled"},{"key":"r0c1","value":0,"h